{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ebe885a1-57c8-4870-b911-8da32f08c464","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class span support** — `T[]` now has an implicit conversion to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` that participates in overload resolution. This causes the compiler to resolve `array.Contains(num)` to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 choice:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** and ref structs are not representable in expression trees, so the expression blows up at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload. Either option works:\n\n**Option A — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B — cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth force the old `Enumerable.Contains` resolution, avoiding any ref-struct involvement in the expression tree.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ac3198bc-acbe-4a06-be23-42bf659e9b6f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and `.Contains()` on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"extension everything\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is about `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]`.\n\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, `int[].Contains(int)` resolves to the LINQ extension method from `System.Linq.Enumerable`. But in .NET 10, 