es to execute an expression tree node that references a method involving `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, it fails because that's not allowed in expression trees. runtime when the expression tree is constructed or compiled.\n\nActually, expression trees with unsupported constructs (like ref structs) typically fail at compile time with CS8640 or similar. But maybe C# 14 has a gap where this slips through?\n\nHmm, let me think about this differently. Perhaps the real issue is:\n\nIn C# 14, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` even inside an expression tree. The expression tree itself might compile to IL fine (since the expression tree is just data), but when you call `.Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`, the **expression tree interpreter** can't handle the `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter, and throws at runtime.\n\nOr alternatively, the expression tree captures the `MethodInfo` for `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`, and at runtime when interpreting or compiling the expression, it fails because it can't convert `int[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in the expression tree evaluation context.\n\nI think the most likely explanation is that C# 14 introduces implicit span conversions, so `int[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`. During overload resolution for `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` because the span conversion is more specific. But expression trees can't represent operations involving ref structs like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so this fails at runtime when the expression tree tries to execute.\n\nThe solution is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload resolution path.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the exact mechanism—the user said \"runtime\" error, which could happen if the expression tree is built dynamically and the interpreter encounters a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter it can't handle. Or it could be that recompiling with C# 14 changes which overload gets selected, and the new `MemoryExtensions.Contains` path fails at runtime when the expression tree is interpreted. because it can't handle ref structs. This is actually a known issue with C# expression trees—they've historically had gaps where the compiler allows constructs that fail at runtime.\n\nLet me think through this more carefully. The .NET 10 / C# 14 \"first-class span\" feature adds implicit conversions from arrays to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` that participate in overload resolution. So `int[].Contains(int)` would now resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<int>`, but the compiler might not have caught that this is problematic in expression tree contexts.\n\nThe issue is likely that the compiler is selecting the span overload even though expression trees can't represent ref struct parameters, creating a mismatch between what compiles and what actually works at runtime.","outputTokens":3203},"id":"27c0b8c5-bd29-4d68-bec6-952dc4e595ca","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:36:44.057Z","parentId":"26aafce9-8e73-45db-8249-26766ccd1fe2"}
